    </div>

    <!-- Section 2: What's inside -->
    <h2 class="section-title">What's inside the EK10</h2>
    <div class="feature-grid">
      <div class="feature-card">
        <span class="feature-card-title">Brain — BBC micro:bit</span>
        <p class="feature-card-text">The world's most trusted educational computer — used in schools across the UK, Europe and Asia. Your child programs it with colorful blocks; at home, the free software keeps working.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="feature-card">
        <span class="feature-card-title">Drive — Tank tracks</span>
        <p class="feature-card-text">Dual motors with independent tank-track drive. The EK10 drives, turns on the spot, reverses — and climbs terrain that wheels can't.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="feature-card">
        <span class="feature-card-title">Eyes — Laser distance sensor</span>
        <p class="feature-card-text">A time-of-flight laser sensor (the same technology as in robot vacuums) lets the rover measure distance and stop precisely at its target.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="feature-card">
        <span class="feature-card-title">Gripper module</span>
        <p class="feature-card-text">A servo-powered gripper that picks up, carries and places objects on the Mars surface.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="feature-card">
        <span class="feature-card-title">Drill module</span>
        <p class="feature-card-text">Swappable with the gripper: a drill attachment that breaks the terrain to prepare the ground for planting. Modular design — kids swap tools like real mission engineers.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="feature-card">
        <span class="feature-card-title">AI Vision camera</span>
        <p class="feature-card-text">A trainable machine-vision camera. Kids teach it themselves — at the press of a button — to recognize objects and colors. All AI runs on the device itself: no cloud, no internet, no data leaves the rover.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="feature-card" style="grid-column: 1 / -1;">
        <span class="feature-card-title">Chassis — LEGO-compatible Technic</span>
        <p class="feature-card-text">Built by hand from LEGO-compatible Technic elements. No glue, no screws — pins and snap-fits. At home, it connects with any LEGO your child already owns.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Section 3: 5-day build -->
    <h2 class="section-title">One rover. Five days. New powers every day.</h2>
    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="timeline-day"><span class="timeline-label">Day 1</span><span class="timeline-text">Chassis, tracks and motors: the EK10 drives</span></div>
      <div class="timeline-day"><span class="timeline-label">Day 2</span><span class="timeline-text">The gripper: it grabs and carries</span></div>
      <div class="timeline-day"><span class="timeline-label">Day 3</span><span class="timeline-text">The drill: it breaks ground and plants</span></div>
      <div class="timeline-day"><span class="timeline-label">Day 4</span><span class="timeline-text">The AI camera: it sees and recognizes</span></div>
      <div class="timeline-day"><span class="timeline-label">Day 5</span><span class="timeline-text">The full mission: drive, find, turn, plant — on its own</span></div>
    </div>
    <p class="timeline-closing">Every child builds their own EK10 from components. No two are identical. By Friday, it's a working robot — and it's theirs.</p>

    <!-- Section 4: Specifications -->
    <h2 class="section-title">Specifications</h2>
    <table class="spec-table">
      <tr><td>Model</td><td>CreatorPort EK10</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Controller</td><td>BBC micro:bit V2 + motor expansion board</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Drive</td><td>2× DC gear motors, tank-track drive, independent control</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Gripper</td><td>360° servo, two-rack mechanism, modular mount</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Drill</td><td>Modular attachment, swappable with gripper</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Distance sensing</td><td>Laser time-of-flight sensor (VL53L0X class)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>AI vision</td><td>Trainable on-device camera — object, color & line recognition, no cloud</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Chassis</td><td>LEGO-compatible Technic elements, tool-free assembly</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Power</td><td>Rechargeable battery (USB charging)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Programming</td><td>Block-based (MakeCode), free, runs in any browser — no installation</td></tr>
      <tr><td>In the box</td><td>Complete rover incl. all electronics, sensor, camera*, charging cable, quick-start guide for home</td></tr>
    </table>
    <p class="spec-footnote">*Final module configuration may vary slightly — every EK10 leaves camp fully working and complete.</p>

    <!-- Section 5: Take it home -->
    <h2 class="section-title">Take it home. Keep building.</h2>
    <p class="rover-text">The EK10 — including all electronics, motors, sensors and the micro:bit — belongs to your child. The programming software is free and runs in any browser, so the missions continue at home: new programs, new attachments, new ideas. And because the chassis is LEGO-compatible, every brick in your home just became rover parts.</p>
    <ul class="check-list">
      <li>✓ Free software, works on any computer at home</li>
      <li>✓ LEGO-compatible — extend it with bricks you already own</li>
      <li>✓ Quick-start guide + WhatsApp support from the engineer</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- Section 6: Safe by design -->
    <h2 class="section-title">Safe by design</h2>
    <p class="safe-text">All soldering, wiring and tricky prep is done before camp by our engineer. Children work with safe, pre-prepared components and never handle hot tools. Programming is done with colorful blocks and icons — no reading or typing required. If your child can stack LEGO, they can build and program the EK10.</p>
